SIMPLE: tungsten
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Tungsten
<hw>Tung"sten</hw> <pr>(t⟦ucr⟧ng"st⟦ecr⟧n)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Sw.
<ets>tungsten</ets> (cf. Dan. <ets>tungsteen</ets>, G.
<ets>tungstein</ets>); <ets>tung</ets> heavy (akin to Dan.
<ets>tung</ets>, Icel. <ets>⟦thorn⟧ungr</ets>) + <ets>sten</ets> stone.
See <er>Stone</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A rare
element of the chromium group found in certain minerals, as wolfram and
scheelite, and isolated as a heavy steel-gray metal which is very hard
and infusible. It has both acid and basic properties. When alloyed in
small quantities with steel, it greatly increases its hardness. Symbol W
(<xex>Wolframium</xex>). Atomic weight, 183.6. Specific gravity,
18.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Min.)</fld> <def>Scheelite, or calcium
tungstate.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Tungsten ocher</b></col>, <it>or</it>
<col><b>Tungstic ocher</b></col></mcol> <fld>(Min.)</fld>,
<cd>tungstite.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tungstenic</ent>⟦br⟧
